A heights vector is given, with only one global peak, no local peaks. Identify the peak most efficiently.

Input:
vector

Output:
peak value

Solution:
Divide et Impera is wanted, knowing that we need to find a value that is a) unique and b) the maximum among the rest.
The common approach (not time-efficient) would be sorting the vector and obtaining the last element. However, a binary search-approach shortens the time to O(logn).
The check is for ascending/ descending order, to know in which remaining part of the vector to look next.

Complexity:

T: O(logn)  // binary search
S: O(1) // no additional structures used
